<div class="content">
    <section>
        <p>
            Recently, one of our data flows that was heavily relying on Postgres,
            started to fail, with the main reason being Postgres going out of
            memory. We decided to scale up our already expensive RDS instance, but
            we quickly realized that, on top being of being expensive, that still
            wasn't enough. It all changed when one of my colleagues suggested to
            update our flow to use the Postgres <span class="keyword">COPY</span>
            command rather than <span class="keyword">INSERT</span> statements.
            The performance improvement was spectacular. In fact, so spectacular,
            that I decided I had to know more about it. This article tells my
            experience with the Postgres <span class="keyword">COPY</span>
            command and summarizes what I've come to learn about it.
        </p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h3>What <span class="keyword">COPY</span> is all about</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="keyword">COPY</span> moves data between PostgreSQL
            tables and standard file-system files. <span class="keyword">COPY TO</span>
            copies the contents of a table to a file, while
            <span class="keyword">COPY FROM</span> copies data from a file to a
            table, appending the data to whatever is in the table already.
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine having a <span class="datapoint">users</span> table created
            as follows:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-sql">{% include "articles/pg_copy_command/users_table.sql" %}</code></pre>
        <p>
            The <span class="keyword">COPY FROM</span> command allows to load
            data from a file into the <span class="datapoint">users</span> table:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-sql">{% include "articles/pg_copy_command/copy_from.sql" %}</code></pre>
        <p>
            Similarly, the <span class="keyword">COPY TO</span> command allows
            to unload data from the <span class="datapoint">users</span> table
            into a file:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-sql">{% include "articles/pg_copy_command/copy_to.sql" %}</code></pre>
        <p>
            Postgres offers a rich syntax to handle different file formats,
            file headers, field delimiters, encoding, and more. Checkout the
            <a href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-copy.html">
                official documentation
            </a>
            for more details. Many other database systems with SQL-esque dialects
            also support some form of copy, including Redshift, Snowflake,
            CockroachDB, MySQL, and plenty of others. Certain systems like
            Snowflake allow you to load / unload data not just from / to a
            filepath, but also from / to Amazon S3, Google Cloud Storage, or
            Microsoft Azure.
        </p>
        <p>
            This article deals with the Postgres implementation of the
            <span class="keyword">COPY</span> commands, when to use them and why
            they perfom as well as they do.
        </p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h3>The interface to Postgres</h3>
        <p>
            Before jumping into the <span class="keyword">COPY</span> internals,
            let me spend a couple of words on
            <span class="datapoint">
                <a href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/libpq.html">libpq</a>
            </span>,
            the gateway to Postgres.
            <span class="datapoint">libpq</span> is the the Postgres native C client
            library. It is the fundamental API used to talk to a Postgres server
            from client programs. It implements the Postgres frontend/backend
            protocol and provides all the core functions needed to:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Establish and control connections to a Postgres database server
            </li>
            <li>
                Send SQL commands
            </li>
            <li>
                Receive and process results returned by the server
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            In other words, libpq is the official C application programmer’s
            interface to Postgres. Programs written in C can call functions in
            libpq to interact with the database backend directly. It’s also the
            underlying implementation for many higher-level language interfaces,
            drivers and bindings. That means that even when using another
            language, at the lowest level the client library talking to the
            database server is often <span class="datapoint">libpq</span>.
        </p>
        <p>
            To truly understand the Postgres <span class="keyword">COPY</span>
            command, it is necessary to understand how
            <span class="datapoint">libpq</span> and the Postgres server
            communicate over the frontend/backend protocol, and particularly how
            bulk data is streamed between a client using
            <span class="datapoint">libpq</span> and the Postgres backend.
        </p>
    </section>
